https://www.npmjs.com/package/markdown-spellcheck checks for typos in a .md Markdown file and stores the custom dictionary entries in a .spelling file.

The good news is that "markdown" is a pretty vague format, so we can spellcheck .ftl files without too many issues:

```sh
$ npx markdown-spellcheck -n -a -x --en-us ./locales/en/email-strings.ftl -r
```

**NOTE:** The <kbd>-r</kbd> flag is for "report mode". If you remove it, the script will run in "interactive mode" and let you manually correct typos or add words to your dictionary.

Other flags are:

- **Ignore numbers** (<kbd>-n</kbd>, <kbd>--ignore-numbers</kbd>)
   Ignores numbers like 1.2 and 1,2.4.
- **Ignore acronyms** (<kbd>-a</kbd>, <kbd>--ignore-acronyms</kbd>)
   Ignores acronyms like NPM. Also ignores numbers. Does not ignore single letters e.g. U.
- **No suggestions** (<kbd>-x</kbd>, <kbd>--no-suggestions</kbd>)
   Suggestions are slow at present, so use this to remove them.


But the main problem is that it really hates the key=value syntax in the .ftl files since it expects that the keys (ie: "layout-social") are valid dictionary words:

```ini
layout-social = Social
```

The following little script will scan a directory of .ftl files, and copy all the key values into a .spelling file:

```js
const fs = require("fs");

const {parse} = require("fluent-syntax");
const glob = require("glob").sync;

main();

async function main() {
  const ftlDist = fs.readFileSync(".spelling-dist", "utf-8");
  const files = glob("./locales/en/*.ftl");
  const keys = files.reduce((acc, file) => acc.concat(` - ${file}`, fetchFtlKeys(file), "\n"), []);
  console.log(keys.concat(ftlDist).join("\n").trim());
}

function fetchFtlKeys(file) {
  const ftl = fs.readFileSync(file, "utf-8");
  const keys = [];
  parse(ftl).body.forEach(item => {
    switch (item.type) {
      case "Message":
      case "Term":
        keys.push(item.id.name);
        break;
      case "GroupComment":
        // ignore
        break;
      default:
        console.log(`UNKNOWN TYPE: ${item.type}`);
        break;
    }
  });
  return keys.sort();
}
```

